History.Early Development:
[[File:Living city heraldry.png|thumb|''The Living City logo.''|313x313px]]Living City began its life in 1986 as the RPGA's "City Project", a coordinated effort to "create a composite fantasy city out of submissions from the membership [&hellip;] that we all can use, and we all will have contributed a little something to".{{Cite polyhedron/30/Notes from HQ}} [[James Ward]] and [[Harold Johnson]] were the primary creative forces behind the project.{{Cite polyhedron/88/Notes From HQ: Living City Growing Pains}} As of July of that year, few details had been nailed down except that the city should be "either a seaport or a river town to facilitate trade [&hellip;] located in a temperate zone". A contest to name the city was announced in [[Polyhedron 30|''Polyhedron'' #30]].{{Cite polyhedron/31/Notes from HQ}} A shortlist of candidates was presented in [[Polyhedron 32|''Polyhedron'' #32]],{{Cite polyhedron/32/Name-the-Living-City-Contest}} and the final results were announced in [[Polyhedron 36|''Polyhedron'' #36]]. The winner was "Ravensgate", but this turned out to already be trademarked by another company. Rather than going with the second-place name&mdash;because they had already commissioned a [[raven]]-themed map for the city&mdash;the RPGA decided to come up with another, to-be-determined name containing the word "raven". It was also announced that the Living City was to be part of the [[Forgotten Realms]], "a little south of the city of [[Tantras]] [&hellip;] on The [[Dragon Reach]]".{{Cite polyhedron/36/Notes from HQ}} The city's final name was settled on shortly after: Ravens Bluff.{{Cite polyhedron/37/Notes from HQ}}

The very first Living City article, "On the Road to the Living City", was published in [[Polyhedron 34|''Polyhedron'' #34]], written by [[Jean Rabe]] with contributions from [[Michael Lach]]. In addition to introducing the first two mini-adventures set in the Living City, the article announced a full campaign book was in the works alongside a "monthly newsletter which will feature current events within the city".{{Cite polyhedron/34/On the Road to the Living City|6}} The first Living City tournament adventure, ''[[Caravan (adventure)|Caravan]]'' by James Ward, debuted at Gen Con '87, which ran from August 20&ndash;23, 1987.{{Cite polyhedron/49/Notes from HQ}} and through mail order.{{Cite polyhedron/50/Notes from HQ|5}} Between 1989 and 1990, the Living City kept expanding through regular articles in ''Polyhedron'' and through the release of another sourcebook, ''[[Inside Ravens Bluff, the Living City]]'', but the actual organized play aspect of the campaign was restricted to a single tournament adventure run each year at Gen Con. This changed in 1991 when, citing increased popularity, the RPGA opted to run two different adventures at Gen Con. The tournament was also opened for all RPGA members, not just those ranked as judges.{{Cite polyhedron/58/Notes from HQ}}

This increased popularity came with some growing pains. The early Living City operated on an honor system, with players trusted to maintain their own characters without cheating by adding unwarranted [[magic item]]s or gold to their sheets. In 1993, Jean Rabe noted that this had become a problem, and so the RPGA began tracking which characters received rewards from which adventure. A consortium was formed to oversee Living City specifically, headed by [[Wayne Straiton]].

History.Farewell to the Living City:
The launch of 3{{rd}}-edition ''D&D'' heralded a major change for the Living City campaign. The RPGA struggled to convert the thousands of player characters (and their individual belongings) to the new edition, and ultimately ceased maintaining the campaign. Starting in 2002, the third-party company OrganizedPlay was given a contract to keep Living City running for 3{{rd}} edition.{{Cite polyhedron/170/Farewell to the Living City}}

Near the end of 2002, OrganizedPlay announced that Living City would be split into two different campaigns: one for high-level characters and one for low-level characters. This was intended to help Living City compete with Living Greyhawk, whose "[p]articipation rates [&hellip;] averaged roughly 10 times that garnered by Living City". The high-level campaign would retain "the characters and context that has been created by the thousands of players who have made Ravens Bluff their homes" while the low-level campaign would "concentrate on a new iteration of the Living City campaign that doesn't have to account for nearly a decade of campaign development".{{Cite web |url=http://www.old-oeridians.com:80/livingcity/announcement-lc2003-plans.html |title=Living City 2003 Plans |accessdate=2023-09-10 |author=[[Ryan Dancey]] |date=2002-11-02 |publisher=OrganizedPlay |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021214075224/http://www.old-oeridians.com:80/livingcity/announcement-lc2003-plans.html |archivedate=2002-12-14 }}

Organized Play kept this up until the end of 2003, when dwindling interest forced them to drop the Living City contract. In June 2004, the Living City program was formally discontinued, with the RPGA preferring to focus on the [[Legacy of the Green Regent]] and Living Greyhawk campaigns.
